            .</p>
               <p>GEORGE MERCHANT. I live at Grandfield, in Hertfordshire, and <rs id="t18310512-189-viclabel1105" type="occupation">work for Mr. Merchant, in his farm</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310512-189-victim1403 t18310512-189-viclabel1105"></join>. I was near Holywell-lane, Shoreditch, on the 6th of May, with my horse and cart - I saw the prisoner, who asked if I would take a load for her; she had some oysters and perriwinkles with her - she got into the cart; I had a hat there, which was done up in white paper - I saw her with it in her lap in the cart; when I got to the White Hart, in <placeName id="t18310512-189-crimeloc1106">Kingsland-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310512-189-crimeloc1106" type="placeName" value="Kingsland-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310512-189-crimeloc1106" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310512-189-off1103 t18310512-189-crimeloc1106"></join>, I stopped, and asked her for it - she said she had not seen it; I then gave her into custody - I had known her five or six years.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310512-189-person1404">
                  WILLIAM 
                  COOK
               <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1404" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1404" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1404" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Kingsland-road - I am a chandler. On the 6th of May the prisoner came to my shop for a halfpenny worth of tobacco; she had a piece of bacon under her right arm, and a hat in her left hand- she asked me to let her leave the hat for ten minutes, while she delivered the other things; it was then between eleven and twelve o'clock - my house is four hundred yards from the White Hart.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310512-189-person1405">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HENRY COOK
               <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1405" type="surname" value="HENRY COOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1405" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310512-189-person1405" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the son of the last witness. I saw the prisoner get out of Merchant's cart, in Kingsland-road, with the bacon under her arm, and the hat in her hand; I saw her taking the hat out of the cart.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had a heavy load - I set them down at a pitching-block; I went into a public-house -I was rather in liquor; the prosecutor came for a glass of beer - I rode in the cart; the cart was full, and there was a live calf in it - I kept my hand on my bundle to keep it steady; I do not recollect any thing about the hat.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM COOK. She was not the least in liquor.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310512-189-verdict1107" type="verdictDescription">
